<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schellenberg" authorityYear="1926" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Scopelocheiropsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scopelocheiropsis abyssalis" order="Amphipoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abyssalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Scopelocheiropsis abyssalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described and illustrated as lacking a mandibular molar. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendrycks, EA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="2303 - 2368" publicationUrl="10.1080/00222930210138926" refId="B92" refString="Hendrycks, EA, Conlan, KE, 2003. New and unusual abyssal gammaridean Amphipoda from the north-east Pacific. Journal of Natural History 37: 2303 - 2368, DOI: 10.1080/00222930210138926" title="New and unusual abyssal gammaridean Amphipoda from the north-east Pacific." url="10.1080/00222930210138926" volume="37" year="2003">Hendrycks and Conlan (2003)</bibRefCitation>
described new material and indicated the presence of a small molar. We have re-examined one of the syntypes of this species and can confirm the presence of a molar on the type material (see Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 36" captionStartId="F36" captionText="Figure 36. Scopelocheiropsis abyssalis Schellenberg, 1926. Syntype female, 5 mm, ZMB 20319, mid Atlantic Ocean. Whole G 1, G 2, P 4, P 5 after Schellenberg 1926. Scales for P 3, P 7 represent 0.5 mm, remainder represent 0.1 mm." pageId="20" pageNumber="21">36</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
